09171nam a22010935i 9780813550206DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20102010nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135502067 a10.36019/97808135502062doi  a(DE-B1597)529627  a(OCoLC)1135615343  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aHQ756b.P365 2011eb 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a306.874/20863122200aPapa, PhD :bEssays on Fatherhood by Men in the Academy /ced. by Mary Ruth Marotte, Paige Reynolds, Ralph Savarese. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tThinking Stiffs: An Introduction -- tPart One. Fathers in Theory, Fathers in Praxis: Merging Work and Parenting -- tDisney Dad -- tGaining a Daughter: A Father’s Transgendered Tale -- tGifts from the Sea -- tThe Luck of the Irish -- tShifting the Tectonic Plates of Academia -- tHair-Raising Experiences -- tA River Runs through It: Queer Theory and Fatherhood -- tOn Writing and Rearing -- tDoing Things with Words -- tOn Fecundity, Fidelity, and Expectation: Reflections on Philosophy and Fatherhood -- tSheathing the Sword -- tPart Two. Family Made: The Difference of Alternative or Delayed Fatherhood -- tWeighed but Found Wanting: Ten Years of Being Measured and Divided -- tVespers, Matins, Lauds: The Life of a Liberal Arts College Professor -- tHow White Was My Prairie -- tMeniscus -- tOnce Was Lost -- tShared Attention: Hearing Cameron’s Voice -- tAccidental Academic, Deliberate Dad -- tLate Fatherhood among the Baptists -- tBeing a Dad, Studying Fathers: A Personal Reflection -- tSingle Dad in Academia: Fatherhood and the Redemption of Scholarship -- tSuperheroes -- tPart Three. Forging New Fatherhoods: Ambitions Altered and Transformed -- tMaybe It Is Just Math: Fatherhood and Disease in Academia -- tDreaming of Direction: Reconciling Fatherhood and Ambition -- tMaking a Home for Family and Scholarship -- tChange Is Here, but We Need to Talk about It: Reflections on Black Fatherhood in the Academy -- tVocabularies and Their Subversion: A Reminiscence -- tBalancing Diapers and a Doctorate: The Adventures of a Single Dad in Grad School -- tIt’s a Chapter-Book, Huh: Teaching, Writing, and Early Fatherhood -- tPitcher This: An Academic Dad’s Award-Winning Attempt to Be in Two Places at Once -- tOdd Quirks -- tThe Precarious Private Life of Professor Father Fiction Chef and Other Possible Poignancies -- tNotes on Contributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt is not easy raising a family and balancing work and personal commitments in academia, regardless of gender. Parents endure the stress of making tenure with the demands of life with children. While women's careers are derailed more often than men's as a result of such competing pressures, fathers, too, experience conflicting feelings about work and home, making parenting ever more challenging. In Papa, PhD, Mary Ruth Marotte, Paige Martin Reynolds, and Ralph James Savarese bring together a group contributors from a variety of backgrounds and disciplines. They are white, black, South Asian, Asian, and Arab. They are gay and straight, married and divorced. They are tenured and untenured, at research-one universities and at community colleges. Some write at the beginning of their careers, others at the end. But, perhaps most important they do not look back-they look forward to new parental and professional synergies as they reflect on what it means to be a father in the academy. The fathers writing in Papa, PhD seek to expand their children's horizons, giving them the gifts of better topic sentences and a cosmopolitan sensibility. They seriously consider the implications of gender theory and queer theory-even Marxist theory-and make relevant theoretical connections between their work and the less abstract, more pragmatic, world of fathering. What resonates is the astonishing range of forms that fatherhood can take as these dads challenge traditional norms by actively questioning the status quo.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aFather and child. 0aFatherhood. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAugspurger, Mike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBane, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarnhurst, Kevin G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBryant, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampbell, David G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarpenter, Stanford W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Lennard J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDomini, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDu Plessis, Eric H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGabbard, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGelfer, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGray, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaven Blake, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHazucha, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIrvine, Colin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKumar, Amitava, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeak, Jeffrey B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMan Tsao, Ting, econtributor.4ctb4https://i